JSON files

author: “Mhairi McNeill”
date: “4/06/2019”

1 Learning Objectives

  • Understand what a JSON object is
  • Know what a key:value pair is
  • Understand why data is commonly stored in JSON form

Duration - 45 minutes

2 What is JSON data?

JSON stands for ‘JavaScript Object Notation’. JSON is a special form of text data with added structure; in that sense it is similar to CSV, but the similarities don’t go much further

JSON is designed to be readable to computers and by humans. Below you can see an example of a JSON file.

JSON files are designed to work with a range of different programming languages and in different environments. This makes them very useful for moving data, both between applications on the same computer system and between separate computer systems. JSON files are in particularly common on the internet: often the data sent to your computer will arrive in JSON format, and the data sent from your computer to a web server will often be sent as JSON.

All JSON files are made up of two “types” of data structure:

  1. Objects, which are collections of key/value pairs. They are surrounded by curly brackets and the keys and values are separated by colons. Here’s a very basic object.
{
  "name": "Luke Skywalker", 
  "height": "172", 
  "mass": "77"
}
  1. Arrays, which are an ordered list of items. Here’s an example of an array:
[
  "The Empire Strikes Back",
  "Revenge of the Sith",
  "Return of the Jedi",
  "A New Hope",
  "The Force Awakens"
]

Arrays and objects can be combined together to make complicated structures:

{
  "name": "Luke Skywalker",
  "height": "172",
  "mass": "77",
  "hair_color": "blond",
  "skin_color": "fair",
  "eye_color": "blue",
  "birth_year": "19BBY",
  "gender": "male",
  "homeworld": "Tatooine",
  "films": [
    "The Empire Strikes Back",
    "Revenge of the Sith",
    "Return of the Jedi",
    "A New Hope",
    "The Force Awakens"
  ],
  "species": [
    "Human"
  ],
  "vehicles": [
    "Snowspeeder",
    "Imperial Speeder Bike"
  ]
}

3 How to read JSON data in R.

When you read JSON into R it will convert all objects into named lists, and all arrays into unnamed lists.

Have a look at the file colours.json with a text editor (e.g. atom). How do you think this will look when read into R?

Now let’s actually read the file. We’ll be using a package called jsonlite. First install the package.

install.packages("jsonlite")

and load the package. We’ll also be using the readr package to read in the file as character type first.

library(jsonlite)
library(readr)

Reading in JSON works differently from the other file formats that we’ve seen so far. It’s really a totally different kind of data. Everything we’ve seen so far gets read in as a data.frame, but JSON data comes into R as a list because it doesn’t neatly fit in a table format.

Before we parse the JSON, we first need to read it in as a single text string using the read_file() function from the readr package

raw_colours <- read_file("data/colours.json")

This string isn’t very readable:

raw_colours
## [1] "[\n  {\n    \"color\": \"black\",\n    \"category\": \"hue\",\n    \"type\": \"primary\",\n    \"code\": {\n      \"rgba\": [255,255,255,1],\n      \"hex\": \"#000\"\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    \"color\": \"white\",\n    \"category\": \"value\",\n    \"code\": {\n      \"rgba\": [0,0,0,1],\n      \"hex\": \"#FFF\"\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    \"color\": \"red\",\n    \"category\": \"hue\",\n    \"type\": \"primary\",\n    \"code\": {\n      \"rgba\": [255,0,0,1],\n      \"hex\": \"#FF0\"\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    \"color\": \"blue\",\n    \"category\": \"hue\",\n    \"type\": \"primary\",\n    \"code\": {\n      \"rgba\": [0,0,255,1],\n      \"hex\": \"#00F\"\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    \"color\": \"yellow\",\n    \"category\": \"hue\",\n    \"type\": \"primary\",\n    \"code\": {\n      \"rgba\": [255,255,0,1],\n      \"hex\": \"#FF0\"\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    \"color\": \"green\",\n    \"category\": \"hue\",\n    \"type\": \"secondary\",\n    \"code\": {\n      \"rgba\": [0,255,0,1],\n      \"hex\": \"#0F0\"\n    }\n  }\n]"

The function prettify() let’s us read the text, but if we want R to read the text, we pass it into the parse_json() function.

colours <- parse_json(raw_colours)

Now colours is a list.

‘Parsing’ is a common term in computer science. Roughly it means ‘understand by analysing its parts’. We ‘parsed’ the JSON file, because we took the whole lump of text and broke it down into meaningful parts: the breakdown is as defined in the final list.

3.1 Parse to a data frame

A really useful feature of the jsonlite package is that it can convert JSON into data frames. Not every piece of JSON can be converted into a data frame; often JSON represents data which is highly ‘non-rectangular’.

If you have the option to read data in as a data.frame, that’s almost always a better option than a list. R has more tools for working with data frames. In particular the dplyr package, which you will learn about later in the course, is a very powerful data analysis library and it works entirely with data frames.

To parse JSON and return the result as a data.frame (where possible), use the function fromJSON():

colours2 <- fromJSON(raw_colours)

Now colours2 is a data.frame.

class(colours2)
## [1] "data.frame"
colours2

Task - 5 mins

Read the file example.json: first as a list, and then as a data.frame.


Answer

raw_example <- read_file("data/example.json")
example <- parse_json(raw_example)
example_df <- fromJSON(raw_example)

4 How to write JSON data in R.

The jsonlite library doesn’t only read in JSON data, it can also write it out to file too. We do that using the function write_json(). The first argument should be a list or a data frame, the second argument is the path where the JSON file will be saved.

Let’s take the colour_list data set from the course data package and write it in JSON format.

library(CodeClanData)

write_json(colour_list, "data/colours2.json")

Take a look at the JSON file we just wrote (you can use atom for this, or the less shell command). What do you see?

JSON files are meant to be readable by computers and by humans, but this file is not very human readable at all. We can fix this by setting the pretty = TRUE argument, which formats the JSON across multiple lines with helpful indentation. You should also usually set auto_unbox = TRUE: this converts single-element vectors into values, rather than creating single-element arrays.

write_json(colour_list, "data/colours2.json", pretty = TRUE, auto_unbox = TRUE)

Ah, have a look at this JSON file, you’ll find it looks much better!

Task - 5 mins

  • Write the data frame students from the course data package to a JSON formatted file.
  • What is the high-level structure of this file? That is, how does each student entry appear in the file?

Answer

library(CodeClanData)
write_json(students, "data/students.json", pretty = TRUE, auto_unbox = TRUE)

The high level structure is an array in which each element is an object corresponding to a single student.

5 Recap

  • What are the two types of data structure appearing in JSON formatted data?
    Answer Arrays and Objects


  • Which function in the jsonlite package reads JSON files as a list?
    Answer The parse_json() function


  • Which function reads JSON files as a data.frame?
    Answer The fromJSON() function


  • Which function writes out JSON formatted files?
    Answer The write_json() function
